Potato

Target IP: 192.168.170.101

Scanning


From the scans above, there are three TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH (22), HTTP (80), and FTP (2112). I will start my enumeration with the FTP application.

Enumeration

Port 2112: FTP

Since anonymous login is allowed to the FTP application, I downloaded the two files index.php.bak and welcome.msg on my machine.


Viewing the content of the index.php.bak shows the content above. This file contains hardcoded credentails admin:potato.

Port 80: HTTP


We are presented the webpage above. The source-code and image does not provide any useful information.


There is an interesting directory called /admin/. We are presented the webpage above. To access the website, we will need a valid username and password. Using the credentials I obtained from the index.php.bak However, the credentials admin:potato did not work against the HTTP application.


There are three log files located at /admin/logs. It mentions a password was changed recently in log_03.txt. But the username admin is still valid.


Since the application uses strcmp to compare the strings, we can bypass by adding an array to the parameter name; for example, password[]=. After doing this, we obtain the password (serdesfsefhijosefjtfgyuhjiosefdfthgyjh) which is highlighted in the picture above.


And now we have admin acess.


Seems like the host is vulnerable to LFI attacks! If we change the parameter file for the Logs page, we can leverage this attack. The hash of user webadmin is also shown. Maybe we can crack this hash?


I copied the password hash inside a text file called hash.
And using hashcat with the command hashcat -m 500 hash /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt, I cracked the password of webadmin. So we have a login webadmin:dragon.

Exploitation


Firing up the credentials above worked! Now I have a foothold on the machine as webadmin.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like we can run /bin/nice binary on /notes/* with root privileges. We can use path abuse to gain root privileges.


I create a script that spawns a shell inside the user's home directory, changed the permission to be executable, and executed it using /bin/nice binary. And now we have a root shell.

Flags


The local.txt flag which is inside the same directory when we land a foothold on the machine.


The proof.txt flag once I obtained a root shell by using path abuse exploit.
